OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F316A1776211372
OL,3,CWhat is 'Super El Nino' and could it
OL,4,Cmake this summer much hotter?
OL,6,FIn the normal course of things, winds
OL,7,F(known as Trade Winds) blow east to
OL,8,Fwest from South America to Australia,
OL,9,Fsweeping the warm water near the
OL,10,Fsurface of the ocean.
OL,12,FIt then pools around the east coast of
OL,13,FAustralia whilst cooler water close to
OL,14,FSouth America is pulled up from deep
OL,15,Fin the ocean to replace it.
OL,17,FSo, imagine cooler water around the
OL,18,FSouth American side of the Pacific and
OL,19,Fwarmer water close to the Australian
OL,20,Fside.
OL,26,@kD@UTw
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G3/13
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,317,300,200,140,000,100
PN,31604
SC,0004
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F316A1776211372
OL,3,CWhat is 'Super El Nino' and could it
OL,4,Cmake this summer much hotter?
OL,6,FPut simply, the warmed air above this
OL,7,Fwarm water close to Australia rises,
OL,8,Fcondenses and gives rain across
OL,9,Feastern Australasia.
OL,11,FThe cooler, drier air flows back
OL,12,Feastwards across the tropical Pacific
OL,13,Fand falls back towards the ocean over
OL,14,Fthe cooler water.
OL,16,FIt acts like a self perpetuating water
OL,17,Fcycle (officially known as 'The Walker
OL,18,FCirculation').
OL,26,@kD@UTw
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G4/13
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
