PN,31610
SC,0010
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F316A1776211372
OL,3,CWhat is 'Super El Nino' and could it
OL,4,Cmake this summer much hotter?
OL,6,FVery possibly. El Nino tends to
OL,7,Frelease heat from the ocean into the
OL,8,Fatmosphere, giving global temperatures
OL,9,Fa temporary lift - potentially around
OL,10,F1.5C above pre-industrial levels.
OL,12,FAgainst the backdrop of climate
OL,13,Fchange, that extra boost can be enough
OL,14,Fto push the world towards record-
OL,15,Fbreaking warmth.
OL,17,F2024 was, globally, our warmest year
OL,18,Fon record - and yes, it was influenced
OL,19,Fby a strong El Nino event from late
OL,20,F2023 into early 2024.
OL,26,@kD@UTwnD@UTw{D@RTw
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                   G10/13
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,317,300,200,140,000,100
PN,31611
SC,0011
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F316A1776211372
OL,3,CWhat is 'Super El Nino' and could it
OL,4,Cmake this summer much hotter?
OL,6,FIs climate change affecting this?
OL,8,FThat's an area scientists are still
OL,9,Fexploring.
OL,11,FThere are signs that both El Nino and
OL,12,FLa Nina events could be becoming more
OL,13,Fintense, which may lead to more
OL,14,Fextreme swings between floods,
OL,15,Fdroughts and heat.
OL,17,FWhat's already clear is that even
OL,18,F"cooler" La Nina years today are
OL,19,Fwarmer than El Nino years a few
OL,20,Fdecades ago.
OL,26,@kD@UTwsD@`TwtD@FTwzD@AOUzD@HO]zD@OTw{D@
OL,26,ARTw
